cial policy preferences of Democrats and Republicans to the reasons for resistance to affirmative action. Their findings indicate that while crude and explicit forms of racial prejudice may have declined in recent decades, racial stereotypes persist among many whites and exert a powerful influence on the ways they view certain public policies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aRacismxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aRacismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aWhite peoplezUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aWhitesxAttitudesxUnited States. 0aWhiteszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aCarmines, Edward C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCobb, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilens, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Hosea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurwitz, Ion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuklinski, lames H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLayman, Geoffrey C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeffley, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeffley, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPiazza, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSniderman, Paul M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStoker, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013